As an Italian living in Italy right now, LISTEN TO DR OSTERHOLM AND DON'T LET ANY CONFLICTING INFORMATION OVERLAY WHAT HE SAID.


Let me tell you, the difficult thing in Italy in the past weeks has been to have a secure anchor in the sea of contraddictory information out there. Now we're starting to grasp basic virology concepts in order to protect ourselves and our dear ones, but until some days ago we weren't properly informed by the media. That's something you'll probably going to hear:


- some newspapers will say that holding your breath for 10 seconds without effort is a sign you're not infected (that's bullshit: early syntomps are runny nose and fever);
- some newspapers will say to protect yourself with masks at any time (masks are useless unless you have to take care with someone who has the virus OR you're a trained health worker such as doctors, paramedic, nurse and so on; plus, there will be mask shotages: leave them to the ones who need them);
- some newspapers will say to go out for a walk because mental health is just as important as your physical health (no, it's not: you can cure your mind when this shitshow is over, for now stay at home: you have the internet at your disposal, fucking use it);
- some newspaper will say that it's "just as a normal flu" (yeah it is, for 80% of the population: the other 20% is basically dead if you do anything about it).


I can't stress this enough: LISTEN TO THE DOCTOR AND STICK ON WHAT HE SAID IN THIS VIDEO: IF POSSIBLE, SHARE THIS VIDEO TO EVERYONE. IF YOUR GOVERNMENT SAYS SOMETHING DIFFERENT REGARDING THE TOPICS HE DISCUSSED DO NOT BELIVE SHIT. IF SOMETHING NEW COMES UP (like a miracolous new cure or something like that) LOOK UP FOR SOURCES IN MEDICAL JOURNALS FIRST BEFORE BELIEVING ANYTHING.


You're lucky enough to have us, Italians, as an example on what to do: don't waste this opportunity like the UK is doing right now. Imma be honest, as a healthy 25 year old Muay Thai practitioner at first I didn't believe this virus was going to hurt me or the nation so badly. Boy, was I wrong. I'm OK even if I catch the virus, but what about everyone else? My friend has asthma: what happens if I pass the virus to him? My grandmas are both over 85, but they can statistically live over a 100 years easily without wishing to die first (I'm Sardinian, biggest over 100 concentration in the entire world after Okinawa), why rob them of 15 years? Even my parents are approaching 60, for Christ's sake. Is a walk worth my parents? No, it's fucking not worth it, so I stay at home and I follow what the WHO says. Oh, and don't be fucking dicks at the store: buy the shit you need and then leave without stockpiling for a fucking nuclear winter. The situation is serious, but we aren't unleashing the fucking Apocalypse on each other. Be responsible and good luck

snippet.textDisplay:
Good news about our dependence on other governments for our medicines. According to The Epoch Times (see link below): "A U.S. official said he is preparing an executive order to hand to President Donald Trump that would help relocate medical supply chains from overseas to the United States, as the coronavirus outbreak exposes the vulnerabilities of foreign supply chains.

White House trade adviser Peter Navarro, director of the Office of Trade and Manufacturing Policy, told CNBC that the United States is heavily dependent on the global supply chain “not just for its medicines but for its medical supplies and medical equipment.”

“The essence of the order ... is to bring all of that home so that we don’t have to worry about foreign dependency,” he said in a March 16 interview, adding that 70 percent of the ingredients used in advanced pharmaceuticals “comes from abroad.”

Navarro didn’t specifically name which foreign countries, but experts have long pointed to U.S. dependence on China. Rosemary Gibson, a senior adviser at the Hastings Center, a bioethics research institute, and the co-author of “China Rx: Exposing the Risks of America’s Dependence on China for Medicine,” told The Epoch Times previously that it’s “a risk to our national security.”

“For prescription drugs, 90 percent of the core ingredients, the chemicals, and other ingredients depend on China,” Gibson said.

Navarro said the departments of Veterans Affairs, Health and Human Services, and Defense buy significant amounts of medical equipment, and “we need to have them buy that from American producers on American soil.”

He noted that the current demand for medical masks exposes the pitfalls of foreign supply chains.

Earlier this month, the Trump administration granted exemptions from tariffs on medi- cal products imported from China, which include protective masks and medical gloves.

The issue is also receiving bipartisan concern from lawmakers. Sens. Marsha Blackburn (R-Tenn.) and Bob Menendez (D-N.J.) recently introduced legislation that would boost U.S. manufacturing of active pharmaceutical ingredients (APIs) that are needed to form prescription drugs. Their legislation proposes an additional $100 million in funding to boost U.S. pharmaceutical manufacturing.

Currently only 28 percent of pharmaceutical ingredient facilities making APIs for the U.S. market are in the United States.

The remaining 72 percent of API manufacturers supplying the U.S. market are outside the country, including 13 percent in China, according to the Drug, Chemical & Associated Technologies Association. The number of Chinese facilities has more than doubled since 2010.

“The COVID-19 is a real health emergency and we have to do everything in our power to increase our preparedness and response,” said Menendez in a statement. “This bipartisan proposal will do that by encouraging drug manufacturers to partner with our best minds in higher education on new advancements, creating good jobs and increasing the national production of vaccines and drugs that can save lives.”
